<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1919,2016]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,391]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1919,1944]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[328,585,1919,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bithynicus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[328,585,1919,1943]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">Hydroporus bithynicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[592,656,1920,1944]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[592,656,1920,1944]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has to be included among the species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1161,1324,1919,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[1161,1324,1919,1943]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="41">H. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Fery" box="[220,352,1955,1980]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" refString="Fery, H. (1999) Revision of a part of the memnonius - group of Hydroporus Clairville, 1806 (Insecta: Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) with the description of nine new taxa, and notes on other species of the genus. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien Serie B Botanik und Zoologie, 101 B, 217 - 269." type="journal article" year="1999">
Fery (
<number box="[286,344,1955,1979]" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" value="1999.0">1999</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
as it has uniform pale colour, lateral depressions at the base of the pronotum with a deeper punctation, a dorsally symmetric male aedeagus and the female gonocoxa do not have an angularity on the inner side (
<bibRefCitation author="Fery" box="[158,278,151,175]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" refString="Fery, H. (1999) Revision of a part of the memnonius - group of Hydroporus Clairville, 1806 (Insecta: Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) with the description of nine new taxa, and notes on other species of the genus. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien Serie B Botanik und Zoologie, 101 B, 217 - 269." type="journal article" year="1999">
Fery 
<number box="[218,278,151,175]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Of the known species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[613,776,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[613,776,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">H. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup, 
<taxonomicName box="[900,1048,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bithynicus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[900,1048,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">H. bithynicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1055,1118,152,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1055,1118,152,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is the flattest, narrowest and more parallel sided. The eyes are also smaller than in the other two species, which is particularly evident in ventral view. The aedeagus has also a characteristic shape, unlike 
<taxonomicName box="[830,996,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[830,996,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">H. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ghidini, 1958" authorityName="Ghidini" authorityYear="1958" box="[1056,1381,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanfilippoi">
<emphasis box="[1056,1213,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">H. sanfilippoi</emphasis>
Ghidini, 
<number box="[1325,1381,223,247]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" value="1958.0">1958</number>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Fery" box="[151,269,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" refString="Fery, H. (1999) Revision of a part of the memnonius - group of Hydroporus Clairville, 1806 (Insecta: Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) with the description of nine new taxa, and notes on other species of the genus. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien Serie B Botanik und Zoologie, 101 B, 217 - 269." type="journal article" year="1999">
Fery 
<number box="[209,269,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 68, 70).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">Description.</emphasis>
Total length 
<number box="[499,533,295,319]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" value="3.7">3.7</number>
–4.0 mm, maximum width 
<quantity box="[849,990,295,319]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.7">1.7–1.8 mm</quantity>
. Body elongate, narrow, sides parallel; lateral outline almost continuous; pronotum slightly wider than base of elytra, as wide as maximum width of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[159,225,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1991,2014]" captionTargetBox="[335,1260,242,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[290,1297,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, NMW, photo: M. Brojer)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279859/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,225,367,391]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Colour uniformly testaceous, ventral side darker.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279862/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" targetBox="[153,1434,464,1888]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1917,2008]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,1917,1940]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">FIGURES 7–9.</emphasis>
Habitat of 
<taxonomicName box="[430,662,1918,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bithynicus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[430,662,1918,1940]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName box="[430,551,1918,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hydroporus</taxonomicName>
bithynicus
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[669,726,1918,1939]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[669,726,1918,1939]" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
; 7) detail of the spring in which all specimens were found; 8) general view of the stream between Yeniçaga and Mengen; 9) two of the authors (P. Aguilera and C. Hernando) next to the spring (photos: I. Ribera).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[274,346,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1991,2014]" captionTargetBox="[335,1260,242,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[290,1297,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, NMW, photo: M. Brojer)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279859/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[361,378,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">2</figureCitation>
): wide; surface finely microreticulated, with polygonal, isodiametric cells; covered with very fine, dense punctation; space between punctures 
<number box="[712,754,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
times wider than their diameter. Two small clypeal fossae; periocular area slightly depressed. Eyes small, not prominent. Maximum diameter of eye (seen from above) ca. 
<number pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="11.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="11.0">11– 12</number>
ommatidia (
<quantity box="[325,427,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.937" metricValueMax="4.064" metricValueMin="3.81" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" unit="in" value="15.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="15.0">15–16 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[436,592,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanfilippoi">
<emphasis box="[436,592,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">H. sanfilippoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); surface of ommatidia transparent, pigmented area below cuticle smaller than area covered by ommatidia (
<figureCitation box="[525,595,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[578,595,295,319]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[327,401,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1991,2014]" captionTargetBox="[335,1260,242,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[290,1297,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, NMW, photo: M. Brojer)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279859/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[418,435,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">2</figureCitation>
): transverse; sides strongly bordered, slightly arched. Surface microreticulate, stronger and with larger cells than on head; punctation on disk sparser and stronger than on head; near posterior angles punctation denser, with a more rugose appearance. Anterior margin with irregular row of coarse punctures. Anterior angles with a group of very long setae. 
<collectingCountry box="[639,695,439,463]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Hind</collectingCountry>
wings apparently well developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[283,350,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1991,2014]" captionTargetBox="[335,1260,242,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[290,1297,193,1947]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, NMW, photo: M. Brojer)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279859/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[336,350,476,500]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
): parallel sided, maximum width behind middle; surface covered with dense and strong punctation; microreticulation strong, cells wider than on pronotum and head, isodiametric. Without regular rows of punctures; with some isolated coarser punctures with setae less erect that those of regular punctures, forming loose series on the elytra. Margins with a series of very long setae, from shoulder to apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Ventral darker than dorsal side; metaventrum and first two or three abdominal ventrites dark brown; surface of metaventrite covered with regular, coarse and sparse punctation, space between punctures ca. 
<number box="[1223,1237,655,679]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
times wider than their diameter; covered by strong reticulation, cells slightly transverse (
<figureCitation box="[964,1034,692,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[1018,1034,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Abdominal ventrites with weaker punctation, more disperse; surface microreticulated, with smaller cells than on metaventrite (
<figureCitation box="[1186,1255,727,751]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[1239,1255,727,751]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of metacoxal process slightly sinuate, medially protruded backwards (
<figureCitation box="[977,1045,764,788]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1727,1750]" captionTargetBox="[299,1281,201,1691]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[293,1291,193,1706]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 3. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 2) head and pronotum; 3) detail of the metacoxa (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279860/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[1029,1045,764,788]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" box="[199,1159,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Male: pro- and mesotarsi slightly dilated; claws unmodified. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[1059,1154,799,823]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1791,1814]" captionTargetBox="[314,1291,272,1759]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[285,1301,193,1770]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 6. Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n. (paratype male, DNA voucher specimen MNCN-AI 782); 4) median lobe of the aedeagus, lateral view; 5) median lobe of the aedeagus, ventral view; 6) right paramere, lateral view. Scale bar: 1 mm (photos: A. Castro)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279861/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Figs 
<number box="[1114,1154,799,823]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4-6</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="43" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,836,860]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Bithynia, ancient kingdom of the NW coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[1034,1130,836,860]" name="Turkey" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
and Roman province. The specific epithet is an adjective in the nominative singular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="43" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,498,907,932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
So far only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[824,872,909,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
locality, a fast-flowing stream in a well preserved mixed forest in north-west 
<collectingCountry box="[465,545,943,967]" name="Turkey" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[562,668,943,967]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 9" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1917,1940]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,464,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,445,1897]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 9. Habitat of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n.; 7) detail of the spring in which all specimens were found; 8) general view of the stream between Yeniçaga and Mengen; 9) two of the authors (P. Aguilera and C. Hernando) next to the spring (photos: I. Ribera)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279862/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Figs 
<number box="[622,668,943,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7–9</number>
</figureCitation>
). All specimens were found in a small pool with upwelling spring water (ca. 
<quantity box="[271,316,980,1004]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
diameter, few centimetres deep) on the side of the river. The pool had a stony substratum without vegetation, with some algal and bacterial grow, and was fed by underground water upwelling through the bottom (
<figureCitation box="[159,259,1052,1076]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 9" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1917,1940]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,464,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,445,1897]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 9. Habitat of Hydroporus bithynicus sp. n.; 7) detail of the spring in which all specimens were found; 8) general view of the stream between Yeniçaga and Mengen; 9) two of the authors (P. Aguilera and C. Hernando) next to the spring (photos: I. Ribera)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279862/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Figs 7, 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
The habitat and the external morphology, in particular the reduced eye size and pigmentation and the presence of long sensory setae on pronotum and elytra, suggest that the species is an inhabitant of the interstitial water, only accessible in particular circumstances – in this case, an upwelling spring. The other two species of the group, although with an apparently less modified morphology (they are less flat, with larger eyes) have been reported from similar habitats, or, in the case of 
<taxonomicName box="[525,688,1232,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[525,688,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">H. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from deep inside caves (
<bibRefCitation author="Franciscolo" box="[971,1169,1232,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" refString="Franciscolo, M. E. (1979) Coleoptera. Haliplidae, Hygrobiidae, Gyrinidae, Dytiscidae. Fauna d'Italia, 14. Edicioni Calderini, Bologna, 804 pp." type="book" year="1979">
Franciscolo 
<number box="[1110,1169,1232,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1979.0">1979</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Foster" box="[1180,1424,1232,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" refString="Foster, G. N. &amp; Friday, L. (2011) Keys to adults of the water beetles of Britain and Ireland (Part 1). Handbooks for the identification of British insects, Vol. 4 Part 5, 2 nd ed. Shrewsbury, UK, 144 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Foster &amp; Friday 
<number box="[1364,1424,1232,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[350,506,1268,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanfilippoi">
<emphasis box="[350,506,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">H. sanfilippoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sequenced here (Table 
<number box="[777,789,1268,1292]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1.0">1</number>
) was collected in the small pools of a minuscule stream formed by upwelling water while there was heavy rain: short after the specimen was collected the rain stopped and the stream dried out completely. Only after some additional rain during the next days it was flowing again, and more specimens could be found. The preference for very small running water bodies or interstitial habitats seems to be shared between the species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[580,746,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[580,746,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">H. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[762,890,1413,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="memnonius">
<emphasis box="[762,890,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">memnonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[948,1045,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Hydroporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longulus">
<emphasis box="[948,1045,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">longulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups (see below), and has been suggested as a possible reason for the abundance of the local endemics in the group (
<bibRefCitation author="Fery" box="[1111,1232,1448,1472]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" refString="Fery, H. (2009) New species of the Hydroporus longulus - group from Iran, Armenia and Turkey with a synopsis of the group (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 49, 529 - 558." type="journal article" year="2009">
Fery 
<number box="[1172,1232,1448,1472]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hajek" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" refString="Hajek, J. &amp; Fikacek, M. (2010) Taxonomic revision of the Hydroporus bodemeyeri species complex (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae) with a geometric morphometric analysis of body shape within the group. Journal of Natural History, 44, 1631 - 1657." type="journal article" year="2010">
Hájek &amp; Fikáček 
<number box="[151,212,1484,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
